{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Édouard Manet - Le Vieux Musicien.jpg | title=The Old Musician | artist=[[Édouard Manet]] | year=[[1862 in art|1862]] | medium=oil on canvas | height_metric=187.4 | width_metric=248.3 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | museum=[[National Gallery of Art]] | city=[[Washington, D.C.]] }} '''''The Old Musician''''' is an 1862 oil painting on canvas by [[France|French]] [[Painting|painter]] [[Édouard Manet]], produced during the period when the artist was influenced by Spanish art. The painting also betrays the influence of [[Gustave Courbet]]. This work is one of Manet's largest paintings and is now conserved at the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, DC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Collection - The Old Musician|url=https://www.nga.gov/content/ngaweb/Collection/art-object-page.46637.html|website=nga.cov|accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref>
The painting is composed of seven characters in a landscape. The old musician in the center who is preparing to play the [[violin]] is Jean Lagrène, the leader of a local gypsy band.<ref name="manet.org">{{cite web|title=The Old Musician, 1862 by Edouard Manet|url=http://www.manet.org/the-old-musician.jsp|website=manet.org|accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref> To the left is a young girl standing with a baby in her arms, as well as two young boys. In the background, the man in the top hat is the [[rag picker]] and [[ironmonger]] Colardet.<ref name="manet.org" /> At the right, the Oriental man (partly shown) with a [[turban]] and a long robe, represents Guéroult, a "[[wandering Jew]]".<ref name="manet.org" /> Attitudes and clothes of the characters seem to be inspired by [[Diego Velázquez]] or [[Louis Le Nain]].<ref name="manet.org" /> <ref>{{cite web |title=Édouard Manet, les premières œuvres |url=http://www.van-gogh.fr/edouard-manet-premieres-oeuvres-page-2.php |publisher=Van Gogh |language=French |accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Édouard Manet (artist), French, 1832 - 1883, ''The Old Musician'', 1862 |url=http://www.nga.gov/collection/gallery/gg90/gg90-46637.html |publisher=National Gallery of Art |accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref>
The painting contains a series of allusions: the man in the top hat is the same character as ''[[The Absinthe Drinker (Manet painting)|The Absinthe Drinker]]'', painted by Manet some years earlier and who reappears in this painting without any particular reason. The young boy in straw hat, meanwhile, is explicitly inspired by [[Antoine Watteau]]'s ''Pierrot''.
